PUH-BrianMartell The Kerr effect is the instantaneous nonlinear response of a medium where the refractive index n increases with light intensity: n = n₀ + n₂ I (n₂ > 0 Kerr constant, I intensity). Simple picture: •  Linear medium: Light spreads (diffraction/dispersion). •  Kerr nonlinearity: High-intensity core raises n → acts as self-induced lens → focuses beam/pulse. •  Balance: Focusing counters spreading → stable soliton propagates unchanged. In optics: •  Temporal solitons (fibers): Group-velocity dispersion balanced by Kerr self-phase modulation → stable pulses. •  Spatial solitons (bulk/waveguides): Diffraction balanced by Kerr self-focusing → nondiffracting beams. In PUH v25, exact analog: •  Substrate tension ξ and density ρ respond to ripple amplitude → effective n = n₀ + n₂ |u|². •  High-amplitude ripple → local n increase → self-focusing → traps energy into stable twist knot (matter particle).
